        outline: "The term ‘Pigments of Life’ was coined by Alan Battersby to describe a group of ring- or horseshoe-shaped macrocyclic molecules called tetrapyrroles, that hold in their centre a metal ion[1]. These molecules colour our world and are essential in all living organisms; featured members are the green chlorophyll, the red haem, and the red-orange vitamin B12. Iron-containing haem is the most versatile due to the importance of iron redox chemistry in a range of important biological processes. Specialised enzymes degrade haem to recycle iron, producing a variety of haem ‘skeletons’. These haem skeletons are well characterised in animals; they are responsible for the colour of urine and eggshells but are also involved in protection from oxidative damage, in cell regulation, and disease. Recently, pathogenic bacteria such as Staphylococcus aureus[2], Mycobacterium tuberculosis[3], and Escherichia coli[4], have been found to possess non-canonical haem-degrading enzymes that produce unusual haem skeletons that either have biological functions or are metabolic wastes[5]. The project will investigate the different protein families of bacterial haem degrading enzymes, hypothesise about the biological functions, discuss and propose the future directions.",
