        outline: "Bacterial pathogens harvest haem, the pigment of life, an iron-containing cyclic tetrapyrrole cofactor involved in various essential biochemical reactions, from the host to survive and establish successful infection[1]. In humans, approximately 70% of iron is in the form of haem within haemoglobin, which is found in the blood and is responsible for oxygen transport and the red colour[2]. Both humans and bacteria have haem-degrading enzymes that break open haem to release the iron, converting the red/brown pigment into the green-pigmented skeletal product called biliverdin. In humans, biliverdin is further metabolised into yellow and brown pigments, a biochemical process observable in the colour of human bile, bruises, and waste (urine and faecal matter)[3]. How do bacterial pathogens process haem? Using biochemical and chemical methodologies, the project will investigate the enzymatic reactions of a selection of pathogenic bacterial haem-degrading enzymes and their pigment products. The focus will be on mycobacteria, a family of bacteria that includes the notorious M. tuberculosis (M. tb), M. leprae, and the environmental species causing the emerging non-tuberculous mycobacterial infections worldwide. For example, M. tb haem-degrading enzyme is unusual among bacteria because it degrades haem into a purple-pigmented product called mycobilin instead of the green-pigmented biliverdin[4]. The pathophysiological implications of the differences in bacterial haem skeleton pigment are not yet clear[5].",
