        outline: "Sleep is a fundamental homeostatic process in the animal kingdom. In humans, sleep abnormalities are associated with various brain disorders, such as Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson’s disease, autism, depression and schizophrenia. Thus, a better understanding of sleep regulatory mechanisms is extremely important for our health. Over the past half-century, neuroscientists uncovered that sleep is controlled by the collective action of neurons, called neural ensembles, across the brain. However, it remains unclear exactly how such neural ensembles are coordinated in distributed neural circuits of the brain. To address this fundamental challenge, it is essential to monitor neural ensembles across the brain at the single-cell level in real-time in vivo. Recently, a consortium of world-leading researchers has developed novel technology, called “Neuropixels”. Like the technology of Elon Musk’s Neuralink, this Neuropixels consists of a needle-like probe containing hundreds of microscale electrodes. This allows to monitor neuronal activity at the single-cell level across multiple brain regions simultaneously. In this lab-based project, we will adopt this cutting-edge technology to investigate how sleep is regulated by distributed neural ensembles in mice. An objective is as follows: sleep is traditionally classified into two major stages, called rapid eye movement (REM) and non-REM (NREM) sleep. However, this classification is based on coarse measurements of electroencephalograms (EEGs) and electromyograms (EMGs). Given the resolution of Neuropixels technology, we will be able to characterize distributed neural ensembles across sleep-wake cycles in unprecedented precision. Since individual neural activity is highly diverse, we will test the hypothesis that sleep can be classified into multiple sub-states beyond the traditional sleep-stage classification. This will provide insight into the development of a novel diagnostic strategy for sleep disorders and mental disorders. In this project, a student will have an opportunity to learn this state-of-the-art technology in the lab. The student will observe experimental procedures and process high-throughput data for a dissertation.",
