        outline: "P2Y receptors are a family of eight G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs) that are activated by nucleotides such as ATP, ADP, UTP, and UDP. They are present in almost all human cells and play various roles in physiological and pathological processes, including in the regulation of vascular tone, platelet aggregation, response to inflammation, neurotransmission, and pain perception. As is the case with other GPCR, crystal structures have yielded substantial insights into the structure and activation mechanisms of P2Y receptors, though to date, only the tertiary structures of two (P2Y1 and P2Y12) have been determined experimentally. Some groups have thus attempted to gain structural insights of the remaining six receptors, primarily through homology modelling and computational chemistry-based computer simulations supported by mutagenesis studies. Since the publication of the first iteration of AlphaFold in 2020, it has been heralded as a landmark in de novo protein structure prediction. Developed by Google’s DeepMind, AlphaFold comprised an entirely new kind of software, in that it was first and foremost an AI-driven neural network. It was trained using vast quantities of data to make accurate predictions of distances between pairs of residues, and was more powerful than existing methodologies. In mid-2024, DeepMind published the third generation of this software (AF3), which, in addition to further accuracy-improving refinements, is also believed to be able to predict the interactions of proteins, the effects of point mutations, of post-translational modifications and, in some cases, make predictions about the nature of ligand binding sites.",
