        outline: "The silent pandemic of antibiotic resistance was responsible for 1.27 million deaths in 2019. Most of these deaths, 0.9 million, were caused by the six leading bacterial pathogens associated with antibiotic resistant infections; Pseudomonas aeruginosa, E. coli, Klebsiella pneumoniae, Acinetobacter baumannii, Staphylococcus aureus and Streptococcus pneumoniae. This project is focused on P. aeruginosa a major cause of hospital acquired infections such as ventilator associated pneumonia (VAP), bacteremia and catheter-associated urinary tract infections. A major and rapidly growing problem in treating P. aeruginosa infection is antibiotic resistance. Clinical isolates of P. aeruginosa with resistance to nearly all available antibiotics are prevalent worldwide and between 18 and 25% of clinical isolates are multidrug resistant, showing resistance to three or more frontline antibiotics. An alternative strategy for antibiotic discovery is to utilize the narrow spectrum antibiotics used by bacteria for intraspecies competition. In Gram-negative bacteria such as Pseudomonas aeruginosa, Escherichia coli and Klebsiella pneumoniae these take the form of related high molecular weight protein antibiotics (bacteriocins), termed pyocins, colicins and klebicins, respectively. The use of bacteriocins will, in contrast to the use of broad-spectrum antibiotics, allow specific pathogens to be targeted leaving the wider microbial community intact. The devastating impact of conventional antibiotics on the structure, composition and functionality of human microbiomes is now recognised with increased antibiotic use in early life associated with an increased risk of developing chronic inflammatory diseases such as IBD and asthma in later life. The aim of this project is to engineer novel pyocins with a broad activity against P. aeruginosa clinical isolates including antibiotic resistant isolates.",
