        outline: "Infectious diseases caused by microbial pathogens have, until the advent of antibiotic treatment in the 20th Century, been the most common cause of death in humans throughout history (Balloux & van Dorp, 2017). Microbial pathogens also continue to be the major biotic threat to global crop production (Almeida et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2022). Interactions between microbial pathogens and their hosts - both attack and defence - can be mediated by small (e.g. secondary metabolites) and large (e.g. proteins) molecules (Teixeira et al., 2019; Olive & Sassetti, 2016). Genome sequencing produces a very large number of microbial genome sequences, enabling the identification and discovery of many candidate genes whose protein products are expected to mediate interactions between microbial pathogens and their hosts (Davey & Valdivia, 2019; Urban et al., 2022). This allows for extensive and wide-ranging evolutionary studies of proteins involved in pathogenicity. However, understanding the relationship of sequence variation to protein function requires knowledge of 3D protein structure, but experimental structure determination has not kept up the same rate as sequencing approaches. The AlphaFold AI, and variations on AlphaFold, promise great advances in protein structure prediction. They produce, in many cases, candidate structures that are accurate at atomic level to experimentally-derived structures (Jumper et al., 2021). In conjunction with the European Bioinformatics Institute (EBI), the AlphaFoldDB server provides predicted structures for almost all proteins in UniProt (https://www.alphafold.ebi.ac.uk/). This enables the extension of many bioinformatic approaches for investigating relationships between evolution, sequence, and function biologically-important molecules that do not have an experimentally-solved 3D structure, with groundbreaking implications for drug targeting, and understanding fundamental host-pathogen interactions. In this project, up to six students will each work with a different virulence-related protein from an important pathogen species. They will use an AlphaFold-predicted structure for their protein to help interpret its evolutionary history and suggest candidate functional and/or druggable sites. Approaches that might be taken during the course of the project include: - sequence-based search and enumeration of known homologues/orthologues - comparison of structural predictions for related proteins, and structural identification of remote homologues - evolutionary analysis/phylogenetic reconstruction of pathogen proteins - prediction of conserved functional sites by mapping sequence variation onto predicted structure - identification of coevolving sites",
