        outline: "Enterococci are Gram positive bacteria that form part of the healthy gut flora of humans and animals, but they are also important causes of opportunistic infections. Urinary tract and bloodstream infections caused by these organisms are becoming increasingly common in the clinic, with recent data indicating that rates of enterococcal bacteraemia rose from 9.7 cases/100,000 population to 15.9 cases/100,000 population in England between 2013 and 2021. Furthermore, treatment of enterococcal infections is complicated by the fact that these organisms increasing exhibit antibiotic resistance. These factors mean that it is important for us to gain a deeper understanding of both the mechanisms that are important for enterococcal virulence and for the spread of antibiotic resistance. Plasmids are episomal segments of DNA that frequently harbour virulence factors and antibiotic resistance genes. Importantly, plasmids can be transferred between bacteria through Horizontal Gene Transfer (HGT), enabling exchange of pathogenic or resistant traits between highly virulent and benign bacterial strains. These projects will seek to characterise key features of plasmids carried by the two species of Enterococcus most frequently associated with invasive disease: Enterococcus faecalis and Enterococcus faecium. You will use web-based bioinformatic approaches to interrogate the genome sequences of one of these species to determine key features of their plasmids, such as the frequency of plasmid carriage, the type of antibiotic resistance and virulence factors genes associated with their plasmids (e.g. ABRicate, VirProfile2, CARD), and the mechanisms that the plasmids may use for HGT (e.g. oriT Finder, CONJscan).",
