        outline: "Radiotherapy is a widely used treatment for various cancers, often proving highly effective in curing certain cancers, preventing their recurrence, or slowing their progression. However, many cancers develop resistance to radiotherapy. The underlying molecular mechanisms that drive this radioresistance in cancer cells remain poorly understood. Enhancing our understanding of the biological and molecular basis of radiotherapy resistance in cancer cells will help improve this treatment and ultimately lead to better patient response. Cancer metabolism significantly influences how tumours respond to radiation therapy, yet our understanding of radiotherapy's impact on cell metabolism is limited. Recent studies have reported that radiation treatment can induce changes in various metabolic pathways, including those regulating glucose, nucleotide, glutamine, and fatty acid/lipid metabolism, as well as mitochondrial dynamics, potentially contributing to radioresistance. In this project, you will explore the intricate effects of radiotherapy on cancer cell metabolism and investigate how these effects can be modulated to improve the response to radiation. You will compare and contrast existing literature and identify the temporal changes induced by radiation treatment in a metabolic pathway of your choice. This project has the potential to uncover the metabolic changes driving radiotherapy resistance and offers opportunities to propose novel treatment strategies in combination with radiation to improve patient outcomes.",
