        outline: "Classic protein Biochemistry teaches us that structure = function. Whilst this principle is true, what happens when a protein does not have a defined three-dimensional structure? Intrinsically disordered proteins (IDPs), otherwise known as natively unstructured proteins, or transiently structured proteins, account for 5% of the human proteome, and around 60% of all proteins contain at least one disordered region [1]. These proteins and protein regions have significant roles in cell signalling, ligand binding, and are even implicated in human disease [2, 3, 4]. Due to their heterogeneous nature, they are difficult to study using standard structural biology techniques such as x-ray crystallography. However, the advent of protein structure prediction software such as AlphaFold, has enhanced the structural biology toolkit for proteins that can be challenging to study experimentally [5, 6]. This project will start with a literature review of the intrinsically disordered proteome landscape. You will then use AlphaFold to conduct structure predictions using several proteins of your choice. You will then assess the quality of the models produced by AlphaFold and compare them to other predictors of protein disorder using multiple web-based bioinformatics servers.",
