        outline: "Gonadotrophin-releasing hormone (GnRH), also known as luteinizing hormone-releasing hormone, is the main regulator of the reproductive system [1], through its actions on the GnRH1 receptor (GnRH1R). The role of pituitary GnRH receptors in the control of reproductive functions is well established, with emerging roles in hormone-dependent tumours [2], which has led to the development of new ways to target GnRH1R in cancer [3]. This project is part of an ongoing collaboration between Dr Paul Mulheran (Chemical and Process Engineering, Strathclyde), Dr Val Ferro (SIPBS) and the Cunningham laboratory.  Recent work in Mulheran’s group has studied the interactions between native GnRH and its cognate receptor, GnRH1R, which is a G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR). GnRH1R has recently been successfully modelled by the research team, revealing a new mechanism for how GnRH activates it and how analogs could replicate this action. Resolution of the structure of the human GnRH1R has revealed an unusual ligand binding mode [4], however new insights gained from the Mulheran lab suggest that alterations in GnRH1R receptor trafficking may be important for its unique receptor pharmacology.",
