        outline: "Improvements in anti-cancer therapy over recent years have been overshadowed by increasing evidence of toxic side effects of anti-cancer drugs on cardiovascular function. The cellular mechanism(s) of action underlying these toxic effects remain largely unknown and this is a major area of concern for the field of safety pharmacology. This is even more pertinent for patients who may already exhibit signs of compromised cardiovascular function prior to receiving anti-cancer therapy. Agents such as anthracyclines and tyrosine kinase inhibitors are known to cause compromised cardiac function over time and in some cases, can lead to heart failure. Research examining novel mechanisms of action as well as new modes of delivery for anti-cancer agents is of vital importance in improving our knowledge in this area and ultimately, in designing better anti-cancer therapy going forward.",
        aim: "This project will critically assess the literature on anti-cancer drug induced cardiotoxicity. It will look at the evidence for cardiotoxic effects associated with particular categories of anti-cancer drugs and, importantly, will (i) explore underlying cellular mechanisms of action for the cardiotoxic effects and (ii) assess novel or re-purposed therapeutic options that could reduce these cardiotoxic effects in the future. Project Area Pharmacology References Morelli M.B. et al (2022) Cardiotoxicity of anticancer drugs: molecular mechanisms and strategies for cardioprotection. Front. Cardiovasc. Med. doi.org/10.3389/fcvm.2022.847012 Dong J & Chen H (2018) Cardiotoxicity of anticancer agents. Front. Cardiovasc. Med. 5:9 doi: 10.3389/fcvm.2018.00009 Rawat PS et al (2021) Doxorubicin-induced cardiotoxicity: an update on the molecular mechanism and novel therapeutic strategies for effective management. Biomed. Pharmacother. 139:111708 doi: 10.1016/j.biopha.2021.111708 Zhang X. et al (2023) The mechanism and treatment of targeted anti-tumour drugs induced cardiotoxicity. Int Immunopharmacol 117,109895 doi: 10,1016/j.intimp.2023.109895 ",
