        outline: "The increasing levels of antimicrobial resistance in bacterial pathogens is one of the leading threats to global public health. One of the pathogens listed as ‘critical’ priority are the Enterobacteriaceae, including Klebsiella pneumoniae (https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789240093461). Kpn is a gram-negative bacterium that can thrive in the environment and as commensal in the human gut, but is causing a rapidly increasing number of difficult-to-treat infections in hospital-acquired infections and is one of the leading causes of neonatal sepsis in low-income settings (Sands et al 2021). Our increased understanding of its diversity highlighted that Kpn is however a species complex comprised of several species and sub-species (Rodrigues et al 2019); and whilst Klebsiella pneumoniae subsp. pneumoniae is the main cause of infections, ~5-10% of hospital-associated infection isolates diagnosed as Kpn are usually comprised of K. variicola and/or K. quasipneumoniae. However, as the main efforts in research and public health are on K. pneumoniae pneumoniae (Wyres et al 2020), we have limited understanding of which sequence types or subspecies of K. variicola and K. quasipneumoniae are problematic causing within-hospital infections, or if the infectious isolates are just representing the local diversity and no specific sequence types occur repeatedly. You will assess the recent literature for large-scale collections of Kpn genome studies (mainly hospital-associated infection surveillance and large-scale infectious pathogen surveillance), as well as functional or other descriptive studies of these species. You will collect the associated K. variicola or K. quasipneumoniae data, making critical notes of the limitations of each study considering selection criteria and potential biases (patient population, sampling time, selection of isolates based on resistance profiles) and try to account for the significant bias in geographical spread in published data. You will then assess the resistance profiles, hypermucoid virulence factors, capsule- and O-antigen types (putative vaccine targets under development) and sequence types, and formulate a hypothesis whether any specific sequence types (and if yes, describe these) seem to be globally spreading and should be monitored, and critically discuss these in light of the limitations of the respective studies and how much this impacts our understanding of the global picture.",
