        outline: "Fusobacterium nucleatum is an opportunistic pathogen in the oral microbiome and has been linked to poor prognosis in multiple types of cancer, including colorectal cancer. A key pathogenic trait of F. nucleatum is its ability to form biofilms and adhere to the host environment. The genome encodes for a large number of autotransporters which are surface adhesins, i.e. proteins embedded in the bacterial membrane but with surface-exposed domains (Sanders et al 2018). Adhesins can bind to specific eukaryotic epithelial cell receptors and thus allow the bacteria to reside in the respective tissues, or can form tightly linked assemblages with neighbouring bacterial cells that lead to bacteria aggregating as tight clusters, providing protection from the host immune system (Umaña et al 2019). Whilst it is of clear relevance and high interest, the surface proteome of Fusobacteria is however still only poorly studied as the organisms are very distantly related to most other known pathogens, are difficult to grow in the lab, and no genetic system has been developed so far. Genome analyses and comparisons to non-pathogenic close relatives across the Phylum (Fusobacteriota) can give us important insights into putative pathogenicity factors that are not present or not enriched in their non-pathogenic relatives. Outer membrane proteins require a specific machinery to ensure they are correctly folded into the outer membrane. In E. coli, this is performed by the BAM complex which folds simple structures like porins (Noinaj et al 2013), and the TAM machinery which is essential to fold some of the autotransporter families and fimbrial systems (Heinz et al 2015). In an ongoing collaboration with A/Prof. Nicholas Noinaj from Purdue University (Indiana, USA), we could show that Fusobacteria only have a BAM-like machinery which however has features of TAM as well, indicating that one machinery performs the functions of both BAM and TAM as known in E. coli (Cottom et al under revision).",
