        outline: "The human body is packed with blood vessels. Some estimates even suggest that if you could line up all the blood vessels in a human body, then that line would stretch around the circumference of the world twice. Together, the heart and our blood vessels are known as the cardiovascular system, and its main function is to transport oxygen, nutrients, waste products and hormones around the body. But whilst it is the heart that pumps blood around the body, it is our blood vessels that control exactly where that blood goes. Healthy blood vessels can do this because the walls or blood vessels are able to constrict and relax to increase/decrease blood vessel diameter. However, in many human diseases, this blood flow control fails. Control of blood vessel diameter mainly results from the interaction of two different cell types in the blood vessel wall – smooth muscle cells and endothelial cells. It is smooth muscle cells that contract and relax to alter blood vessel diameter. And endothelial cells control this process by releasing vasoactive factors. But the precise mechanisms that allow endothelial cells to direct smooth muscle contaction are not known. In particular, it is unclear what ion channels and plasma membrane receptors are used by either endothelial cells or smooth muscle cells to control blood flow. In this project, you will use publicly available single-cell gene profiling data (e.g., Tabula Muris [1], Tabula Muris Senis [2], EndoDB [3], Betzholtz Database [4]) to define the molecular basis of endothelial or smooth muscle cell function in health and disease. Additionally, you will conduct functional tests on isolated blood vessels to assess the impact of these mechanisms in blood flow control. Understanding these molecular signatures will lay the foundation for identifying new therapeutic targets to treat blood vessel dysfunction in several non-communicable diseases (e.g., cardiovascular disease, diabetes. Alzheimer’s disease).",
